explanation:
To decide whether any pointer in OS_ConsoleOutput_Impl should be const-qualified (MISRA: pointer should point to const-qualified type when possible) the analyzer needs the following symbols:

- OS_console_internal_record_t: The struct definition is required to see the exact type of console->BufBase (element type and pointer/array declaration), and whether any fields are mutable. Whether BufBase is declared as char *, uint8_t *, const char *, etc. determines if the pointer passed could/should be const.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: The macro or accessor used to obtain the console pointer must be known to confirm the returned pointer type (e.g., pointer-to-OS_console_internal_record_t) and whether any qualifiers are applied when fetching the object. This affects whether console (and its fields) are const-qualified.

- OS_console_table: The object/table declaration/type may influence the result type of OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET and the mutability of entries; its definition helps confirm the effective type/qualifiers of the console record returned.

- OS_BSP_ConsoleOutput_Impl: The prototype/definition of this BSP output function is needed to know the parameter type for the buffer (e.g., void *, const void *, char *, const char *). If the BSP function accepts a const pointer, then passing &console->BufBase[...] as non-const may indicate the console buffer could be const; if it accepts non-const, that suggests callers or BSP may modify the buffer, preventing const qualification.

- OS_ConsoleWrite: This higher-level API is a documented caller of OS_ConsoleOutput_Impl (and likely the routine that writes data into the console buffer). Its implementation must be checked to see whether it writes into console->BufBase (i.e., modifies the buffer contents). If other code writes into the buffer, BufBase cannot be const.

- OS_Console_CopyOut: Listed as a callee of OS_ConsoleWrite and likely involved in moving user data into the console buffer. Its definition is needed to confirm whether it performs writes into console->BufBase (again determining if BufBase must be mutable).

Together these symbols let an analyst determine (1) the declared pointer types used here, (2) whether the buffer is ever modified elsewhere (so const is infeasible), and (3) whether the callee expects a const-qualified pointer. From that information one can judge whether pointer types in OS_ConsoleOutput_Impl (notably the pointer into BufBase passed to OS_BSP_ConsoleOutput_Impl and the BufBase field itself) could/should be const-qualified in compliance with the MISRA rule.
